Annual reminder The Juhu Beach Club Cookbook, Indian Spice Oakland Soul with a trio of my @spicewalla masalas make THE best holiday gift for your fantastic foodie loved ones. Stop stressing about gifting and click the BIO link!
***********************
Oh and there’s some pretty great stories about our humble beginnings:

“I felt like my life was hurtling me towards a food truck.  I had quit my job at Google that paid me very well.  I knew what I wanted but had no idea how to make it a reality.  I came up with the name Juhu Beach Club.  I had an idea..it was Indian food….MY Indian food.  I was making things like “Naan-chos” that were not so successful and spending hours and hours trying to perfect Gujurati samosas. I thought I had to find an investor to open JBC.  But that was easier said.  I was doing private catering, food consulting and being a culinary tour guide…and in the meantime working on this concept.”

“The Garage Café… the liquor store across from my apartment in SF.  I had been going there for beer, snacks, scratchers, emergency milk, etc for 6 years.  Joe, the owner, wasn’t totally sure what he was getting into but he said yes.  I would pay him rent…he would clear out half of this kitchen stuff.  And let me run a lunchtime pop-up called Juhu Beach Club Mon-Fri 11am-3pm.”
#startedfromthebottomnowwehere #indianspice #oaklandsoul #juhubeachclub

Shifting the Lens of Food & Wine
@jwinery x @chefpmistry

I recently attended the most impactful food and wine pairing meal I have ever experienced at @jwinery in Sonoma. At the helm of the meal was Chef Preeti Mistry (they/them), a James Beard Foundation nominee and Top Chef contestant. 

Chef Preeti is a queer, Indian, first-generation immigrant chef who has been taking up space in the Bay Area food and restaurant scene for years. Recently, they partnered with J. Vineyards for the “Shifting the Lens” series which spotlighted diverse perspectives that have traditionally been underrepresented in wine country. 

Chef Preeti paired Indian inspired dishes with classic Russian River Valley still and sparkling wines made by Nicole Hitchcock, who was recently named Winemaker of the Year by @wineenthusiast. 

The pairings made you think and question assumptions. The conversation centered around deconstructing and decolonizing the tasting experience while simultaneously building bridges. An inspiring evening all around!

Oh, and we got to see the house falcon!

Last year when I started working with @jwinery on Shifting The Lens, our goal was to make a meaningful impact, and add to the broadening vision of what food & wine pairing can look, feel and TASTE like. Kudos to Chefs Jenny Dorsey and Shenarri Freeman for joining us in creating such a delicious adventure paired with J Wines. The talented J Team including winemaker Nicole Hitchcock, Chef Aaron Meneghelli, Chef Forest Kellogg and myself are gearing up for our 2nd year (!!!) and have exciting news to share later this month. Stay tuned! But for now how about an encore applause to Shifting The Lens Chefs of 2022.
📸: @nikkiritcher & me 😉

Creating beautiful experiences with @jwinery and super talented Guest Chefs this past year for Shifting The Lens was not just a great experience for all our guests that made it to the vineyard, but also the chef camaraderie built behind the scenes. The learning and sharing in the kitchen of different flavors, techniques and the story behind them is all a part of creating a world we want to see. A world full of unique perspectives that are all appreciated and valued for their distinct contributions to a delicious revolution of food & wine.

It was just a year ago I started working closely with Executive Chef Aaron Meneghelli and Estate Chef Forest Kellogg of @jwinery. We were excitedly anticipating our guests chefs of Shifting The Lens 2022, and getting to know one another in the kitchen. 

This week the three of us, along with Winemaker of the Year Nicole Hitchcock are heading to NYC to cook a stellar meal paired with J wines at the James Beard House and announce our 2023 Shifting The Lens Chefs 🙌🏾🙌🏾🙌🏾 🍾🍾🍾
#TeamWorkDreamWork
📸 @nikkiritcher

We will also have our BIG announcement of our 2023 Shifting The Lens Chefs in Residency  It has been such a wonderfully enriching and inspiring experience with Chefs Jenny Dorsey and Shenarri Freeman last year, the joyous journey of learning and sharing our talents and tastes with each other is about to expand even more. Kudos to the whole J Team for their partnership and collaboration to continue breaking down the barriers of the wine & food pairing landscape.

Hey friends I’m cooking in Oakland 🙌🏾🙌🏾🙌🏾
Oakland Black Pride kicks off this years Black Pride Festival with Breaking Bread: A Benefit Dinner offering a seven course tasting menu prepared by Chef Preeti Mistry of the late lamented Juhu Beach Club & Navi Kitchen and contestant on Top Chef Season 6. Dinner @foragekitchen.oak includes three cocktail pairings. Cocktails will have 0% ABV options. Here's a peak at what's on the menu, Hibiscus Pani Puri, Uttapam Waffle, Wild Mushroom Momos, and more delicious offerings. 🥘🤤

Breaking Bread aims to make the culinary contributions of queer people of color more visible and exhibit the many ways that QPOC have been a meaningful part of the restaurant industry. Offering the dining public in the Bay Area, cuisines and perspectives of those in the industry that have largely been muted. Breaking Bread is a nod to QPOC in fine dining who are rarely seen as next in line to be restaurateurs or executive chefs.

*Menu modifications can not be accommodated as the dishes will be presented as the Chef has intended. 

Tix available on @oaklandblackpride website and also link in my bio. 🎟🔗

Proceeds will benefit Oakland Black Pride 501(c)(3), a nonprofit dedicated to empowering LGBTQOC communities.

Pride started as resistance to state violence. Resistance to violence against queer folks means resistance to violence against ALL queer folks and ALL people. The haters are organizing against us in ways that they have not in many decades. They want to make sure we are not free. But they can’t stop us. We have always been here and we are not going anywhere. #pridemonth #transrights 🏳️‍🌈🏳️‍⚧️❤️🧡💛💚💙💜🖤

I’m so joyful announce Chef Selasie Dotse will join me on opening night of the Black Pride Festival🙌🏾💜 We are pairing up to make a delectable seven course tasting menu to benefit Oakland Black Pride. 💫

Selasie is founder of @elade_tk an Oakland-based pop-up restaurant and supper club providing casual and high end dinner parties specializing in West African / Ghanaian cuisine. 🥘

Born in Accra, Ghana and raised in the American South, food was always a large part of Selasie's life. Over the past 5 years, Selasie has worked at several well-known fine dining restaurants across the San Francisco Bay Area and saw the lack of representation of Black / African chefs and their cuisines in fine dining. e le aɖe Test Kitchen was created to be a space for Black folks, by Black folks in the fine dining world. With e le aɖe Test Kitchen, they create memorable dining experiences through culinary storytelling while supporting and showcasing Black talent in hospitality. 🙌🏿

Chef Selasie believes that economic justice in hospitality looks like restaurant owners investing in their employees before the restaurant. That means providing a livable wage, benefits, healthy work-life balance, and possible equity. They said “If you take care of your employees, they will take care of your business. It's that simple.”🤎

***critter spotting, immense nature knowledge & pics thanks to the best nature guide in CR @yahastropic 
I’m not one for bucket lists but I would put this on it if I had one. 🥰🥰🙏🏾🙏🏾💜💜 #puravida #blessed

I am so incredibly proud & excited to welcome acclaimed Chef Ana Castro to Shifting The Lens @jwinery. In only TWO WEEKS Chef Ana will be cooking her 5-course tasting menu paired with J Wines that you don't want to miss!!! (Link in BIO for those ressies). Join us for an unforgettable and delicious Mexican culinary experience rooted in tradition and full of Chef Ana's infectious warmth and whimsy.  Tastings Thur-Sun in the Bubble Room at J Vineyards in Healdsburg 9/14-24. Or join us for one of two VIP dinners Saturday 9/16 or Sunday 9/24 for a dinner followed by a conversation about our industry.

“I really think that we should move away from looking at kitchens as a merry band of misfits. It’s a professional workspace that requires professional conduct.” - Chef Ana Castro on creating a healthy working environment. Chef Ana Castro’s (@anabanana_castro) first week of Shifting The Lens residency @jwinery has been absolutely epic, and the energy in the Bubble Room inspirational. Chef Castro is deepening all of our knowledge on not just pairing wine with her menu and Mexican flavors, but also the history of many different pre- and post-colonial ingredients and techniques. It’s been such a joy to see her cooking her thoughtful and delicious menu along with the J culinary team. And we even had time for a team grape harvest with head winemaker Nicole Hitchcock. Hope you can join us this week Thur-Sun in the Bubble Room. Tix in my BIO.

A Bubble Room tasting menu with Chef Ana Castro...you will laugh, get a bit weepy and have one of the most memorable food & wine pairing experiences. The masa (from @bolitamasa) at the heart of Chef’s menu is both surprising and warmly comforting in every dish. The history and present day wine country would not exist without the expertise and hard work of the Latinx community, and thus Chef Castro’s residency feels deeply resonant with the whole team and our guests. The goal of Shifting The Lens has always been to highlight different cuisines, and chefs of different backgrounds with the goal of creating a more inclusive culture in wine country. Come see us for her second & final week in the Bubble Room @jwinery. Tix in my BIO.

Happy National Coming Out Day to all those who celebrate 😉 I’m still hoping for a day when we don’t need to come out. When we are given the respect to define ourselves without assumed expectations. Being a queer non-binary person is who I have always been. I didn’t have the vocabulary and awareness when I was 4 years old. But it didn’t change who I was and how I felt about myself. With the increased awareness in our present world, we also have increased & continued hate and violence. Just like sexual orientation, gender is fluid, a spectrum. We all express our gender differently, and to hate on anyone because of their personal gender expression is vile. It’s also sad to me that so many ppl are so afraid to step out of these rigid constructs that they turn their own fear into anger and hate towards others. Let’s love each other’s beautiful differences as much as our similarities🏳️‍⚧️🏳️‍🌈#protecttranskids #comingoutday

There’s so much suffering and pain in our world, more than ever right now. It’s hard to feel like it’s not insensitive to post photos of a fun party we threw last week. And yet I think it’s so important that we share joy with each other and remember we are stronger in solidarity than in segregation and apartheid. Last week we put on a little wine dinner @theredwood.wine with myself and Chef @gcaroline510 in the kitchen and three super talented BIPOC women winemakers @drinkmadmarvlus @maryamandcompany @wardfourwines. We built upon the community each of us have been cultivating, in a historically yt and male wine & food industry and it was beautiful. 💜💜💜 
We can all effect change both in our own communities and those thousands of miles away. It starts with solidarity, respect and compassion for ALL. None of us can do it all, and all of us can do something. I added one throw back pic from 2021 when @tiltedshed introduced me to @iammarreya…look how far we have all come friends🥰🥰🥰 We are all stronger and more resilient when we are surrounded by community that can share our struggles and triumphs. That is always my goal whether it’s with folks down the road from me or across the globe. We can fight the ugly hatred that continues to tear our world apart and we can celebrate joy and love and care for each other. In love and solidarity✊🏾🙏🏾💜

Ceasefire now. Solidarity forever. ✊🏾🇵🇸

It’s been a challenging year.  I’m hoping for more joy in 2024. I’ve been really quiet on here because I needed to quiet my mind and spirit. And I have used this time to focus on figuring out what really matters to me. AKA Getting my head right. Thank you to all of you that have been here IRL to show me the love that is possible when you refocus your heart. Wisdom comes from unexpected places sometimes. Recently watching CNN in an interview with Billy Crystal (!!!) had the words I needed: “Sometimes the middles are harder than the lows.” What’s next? IDK honestly, and maybe that’s ok. 

Last night I had the joy of cooking for ppl I love. Something that is core to my needs and how I express love. I made a dim sum inspired menu, cooking a lot of dishes I have never made before. Shrimp & chive dumplings, hoisin 5-spice smoked ribs, Sichuan chicken wings, veggie spring rolls, garlicky gai lan (pork buns were take out 😉). The last time @chumpchi & I threw a NYE party was 1999 to Y2K. I’m really hoping this new year I am able to find the joy. I don’t think any of us can be happy about the continued suffering we are seeing in Palestine, around the world and here at home. But I’m re-dedicating myself to finding the joy, wherever I can.
